-- Cyrela, Light, Petrobras, Sare: Latin America Equity Preview
-- B y   A n d r e s   R .   M a r t i n e z
-- 2010-11-01T06:07:29Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-01/cyrela-light-petrobras-pdg-realty-sare-latin-america-equity-preview.html
The following companies may have
unusual price changes in Latin American trading. Stock symbols
are in parentheses and share prices reflect the previous close.  The  MSCI Latin America Index  gained 1.4 percent to 4,515.59.
In Brazil, preferred shares usually are the most-traded class of
stock. It’s a holiday in Chile, Colombia and Peru today.  Brazil  Cyrela Brazil Realty SA Empreendimentos e Participacoes 
(CYRE3 BZ): Brazil’s biggest homebuilder said third-quarter
contracted sales fell 37 percent to 1.03 billion reais ($606.2
million). The shares rose 3.1 percent to 23.5 reais.  Empresa Brasileira de Aeronautica SA  (EMBR3 BZ): The
company will decide by the end of the year whether it will close
its Harbin Embraer Aircraft Industry factory in China, said
Chief Executive Officer  Frederico Curado . The shares gained 2.2
percent to 12.11 reais.  Light SA  (LIGT3 BZ): Brazil’s second-largest electricity
distributor said BNDES Participacoes SA sold 10.3 million of the
company’s common shares, according to a regulatory filing. The
shares fell 0.2 percent to 21.42 reais.  MRV Engenharia e Participacoes SA  (MRVE3 BZ): Fitch Ratings
raised the credit rating on the homebuilder to AA- from A+. The
shares rose 0.2 percent to 16.6 reais.  Petroleo Brasileiro SA  (PETR4 BZ): The state-controlled oil
company signed an $820 million, 10-year contract to supply
ethanol to Toyota Tsusho Corp, according to a regulatory filing.
The shares fell 1.6 percent to 25.85 reais.  PDG Realty SA Empreendimentos e Participacioes  (PDGR3 BZ):
Argentine real-estate developer TGLT SA raised 220 million pesos
in an initial public offering. The company’s founders and PDG,
which held a minority stake in the company before the sale,
retained control of “almost” 50 percent of the shares,
according to an e-mailed statement. The shares gained 0.4
percent to 21.27 reais.  Telemar Norte Leste SA  (TMAR5 BZ): The company extended for
three months an agreement to negotiate a partnership with
Portugal Telecom SGPS SA. Portugal Telecom announced the deal in
a regulatory filing. The shares fell 0.6 percent to 48.21 reais.  Mexico  Kimberly Clark de Mexico SAB  (KIMBERA MM): The nation’s
largest consumer products company in Mexico plans to sell as
much as 5 billion pesos ($405 million) of bonds, Standard &
Poor’s said in a statement. The debt is rated AAA, S&P said. The
shares rose 2.1 percent to 77.5 pesos.  Sare Holdings SAB  (SAREB MM): The Mexican homebuilder said
it raised 930 million pesos ($75.3 million) by selling 304.9
million shares, according to a statement to the Mexico stock
exchange. The shares gained 2.3 percent to 3.17 pesos.  To contact the reporter on this story:
